{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}} {{Use British English|date=July 2012}}
'''Joanna Mary Boyce''' (7 December 1831 – 15 July 1861), also known by her married name as Mrs. '''[[Henry Tanworth Wells|H.T. Wells]]''',<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/britain/exhibitions/joannamaryboyce/default.shtm Paintings by Joanna Mary Boyce] (Past exhibitions - [[Tate Gallery]], London)</ref> or as '''Joanna Mary Wells''',<ref>{{cite web|title=Biographical details|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=131360|publisher=British Museum|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> was an [[England|English]] painter of [[portrait]]s, [[genre picture]]s, and occasionally [[landscape painting|landscapes]]. She was the sister of [[Pre-Raphaelite]] [[watercolour]]ist [[George Price Boyce]], and was herself associated with the Brotherhood.
==Life== [[File:Boyce bird of god 1861 0c.jpg|thumb|Bird of God (1861)]] Boyce, born in [[Maida Hill]], [[London]]{{sfn|Bryan|1889|p=704}} was the daughter of George Boyce, a former wine-merchant who had found prosperity as a [[pawnbroker]], and his wife Anne.<ref>{{cite book|year=1987|publisher=The Tate Gallery|location=London|author1=Newall, Christopher |author2=Egerton, Judy |page=16|title=George Price Boyce|isbn=9780946590773}}</ref> At the age of eighteen she entered [[Francis Stephen Cary|Cary's art academy]], and afterwards worked under [[James Mathews Leigh]], at his school in Newman Street, London. Her first exhibited work was a life-size head, which appeared at the [[Royal Academy]] in 1855. In the same year she went to [[Paris]], where she joined the ladies' class in [[Thomas Couture]]'s [[Studio|atelier]].<ref name="BritPort">{{cite book|author1=Brian Stewart |author2=Mervyn Cutten |publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|year=1997|title=The Dictionary of Portrait Painters in Britain up to 1920|ISBN=1 85149 173 2}}</ref>
She spent 1857 in Italy, and in December of that year married [[Henry Tanworth Wells]], (later a Royal Academician) in [[Rome]]. Before returning to England, she painted the greater part of ''The Boys' Crusade'', exhibited at the Academy in 1859. Subsequent exhibited works were: ''The Outcasts'', ''The Heather-Gatherers'', ''Do I like Butter?'', ''La Veneziana'', ''Peep-Bo!'', and ''A Bird of God''. This last painting was left complete on her easel at the time of her death.{{sfn|Bryan|1889|p=704}}
Boyce died from complications following the birth of her third child, Joanna Margaret, on 15 July 1861. After her death, [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]] described her as "a wonderfully gifted woman"; another obituarist called her a genius.<ref name=Apollo>{{cite web | url=http://www.apollo-magazine.com/reviews/books/7902388/homage-to-joanna.thtml | title=Homage to Joanna | publisher=Apollo Magazine | date=24 August 2012 | accessdate=December 1, 2012 | author=Poë, Simon | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923023453/http://www.apollo-magazine.com/reviews/books/7902388/homage-to-joanna.thtml | archivedate=23 September 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>
