{{Pfam_box|Symbol=Na_H_antiport_1|Name=Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> antiporter 1|image=1zcd_opm.png|width=|caption=|Pfam=PF06965|InterPro=IPR004670|SMART=|Prosite=|SCOP=|TCDB=2.A.36|OPM family=106|OPM protein=1zcd|PDB={{PDB3|1zcd}}A:4-380,{{PDB3|4CZ8}}}}
'''Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> antiporter A (NhaA) family''' ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.33 TC# 2.A.33]) contains a number of bacterial sodium-proton [[antiporter]] (SPAP) proteins. These are integral [[membrane protein]]s that catalyse the exchange of H<sup>+</sup> for Na<sup>+</sup> in a manner that is highly pH dependent. Homologues have been sequenced from a number of bacteria and archaea. Prokaryotes possess multiple paralogues. A representative list of the proteins that belong to the NhaA family can be found in the [http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.33.1 Transporter Classification Database].

== Structure ==

Proteins of the NhaA family are of 300-700 amino acyl residues in length. NhaA of ''E. coli'' is a homeodimer, each subunit consisting of a bundle of 12 tilted transmembrane α-helices (TMSs).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Williams KA, Geldmacher-Kaufer U, Padan E, Schuldiner S, Kühlbrandt W | title = Projection structure of NhaA, a secondary transporter from Escherichia coli, at 4.0 A resolution | journal = The EMBO Journal | volume = 18 | issue = 13 | pages = 3558–63 | date = July 1999 | pmid = 10393172 | pmc = 1171434 | doi = 10.1093/emboj/18.13.3558 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Williams KA | title = Three-dimensional structure of the ion-coupled transport protein NhaA | journal = Nature | volume = 403 | issue = 6765 | pages = 112–5 | date = January 2000 | pmid = 10638764 | doi = 10.1038/47534 }}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hunte C, Screpanti E, Venturi M, Rimon A, Padan E, Michel H | title = Structure of a Na+/H+ antiporter and insights into mechanism of action and regulation by pH | journal = Nature | volume = 435 | issue = 7046 | pages = 1197–202 | date = June 2005 | pmid = 15988517 | doi = 10.1038/nature03692 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Olkhova E, Hunte C, Screpanti E, Padan E, Michel H | title = Multiconformation continuum electrostatics analysis of the NhaA Na+/H+ antiporter of Escherichia coli with functional implications | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 103 | issue = 8 | pages = 2629–34 | date = February 2006 | pmid = 16477015 | pmc = 1413810 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0510914103 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Screpanti E, Padan E, Rimon A, Michel H, Hunte C | title = Crucial steps in the structure determination of the Na+/H+ antiporter NhaA in its native conformation | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 362 | issue = 2 | pages = 192–202 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 16919297 | doi = 10.1016/j.jmb.2006.07.019 }}</ref>

Molecular dynamics simulations of NhaA enabled proposal of an atomically detailed model of antiporter function.<ref name=":2">{{cite journal | vauthors = Arkin IT, Xu H, Jensen MØ, Arbely E, Bennett ER, Bowers KJ, Chow E, Dror RO, Eastwood MP, Flitman-Tene R, Gregersen BA, Klepeis JL, Kolossváry I, Shan Y, Shaw DE | title = Mechanism of Na+/H+ antiporting | journal = Science | volume = 317 | issue = 5839 | pages = 799–803 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17690293 | doi = 10.1126/science.1142824 }}</ref> Three conserved aspartate residues are key to this proposed mechanism: Asp<sup>164</sup> (D164) is the Na<sup>+</sup>-binding site, D163 controls the alternating accessibility of this binding site to the cytoplasm or periplasm, and D133 is crucial for pH regulation.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gerchman Y, Olami Y, Rimon A, Taglicht D, Schuldiner S, Padan E | title = Histidine-226 is part of the pH sensor of NhaA, a Na+/H+ antiporter in Escherichia coli | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 90 | issue = 4 | pages = 1212–6 | date = February 1993 | pmid = 8381959 | pmc = 45842 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.90.4.1212 }}</ref><ref name=":4">{{cite journal | vauthors = Padan E | title = The enlightening encounter between structure and function in the NhaA Na+-H+ antiporter | journal = Trends in Biochemical Sciences | volume = 33 | issue = 9 | pages = 435–43 | date = September 2008 | pmid = 18707888 | doi = 10.1016/j.tibs.2008.06.007 }}</ref>

== Function ==

Na<sup>+</sup>-H<sup>+</sup> antiporters are integral membrane proteins that exchange Na<sup>+</sup> for H<sup>+</sup> across the cytoplasmic membrane and many intracellular membranes. They are essential for Na<sup>+</sup>, pH, and volume homeostasis, which are processes crucial for cell viability.<ref name=":4" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Radchenko MV, Waditee R, Oshimi S, Fukuhara M, Takabe T, Nakamura T | title = Cloning, functional expression and primary characterization of Vibrio parahaemolyticus K+/H+ antiporter genes in Escherichia coli | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 59 | issue = 2 | pages = 651–63 | date = January 2006 | pmid = 16390457 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2005.04966.x }}</ref> The ''E. coli'' protein probably functions in the regulation of the internal pH when the external pH is alkaline, and the protein effectively functions as a pH sensor.<ref name=":3" /> It also uses the H<sup>+</sup> gradient to expel Na<sup>+</sup> from the cell. Its activity is highly pH dependent.<ref name=":1"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Diab M, Rimon A, Tzubery T, Padan E | title = Helix VIII of NhaA Na(+)/H(+) antiporter participates in the periplasmic cation passage and pH regulation of the antiporter | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 413 | issue = 3 | pages = 604–14 | date = October 2011 | pmid = 21907722 | doi = 10.1016/j.jmb.2011.08.046 }}</ref>

The generalized transport reaction catalyzed by NhaA is:<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.33|title=2.A.33 The NhaA Na+:H+Antiporter (NhaA) Family|website=Transporter Classification Database|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><blockquote>Na<sup>+</sup> (in) + 2H<sup>+</sup> (out) ⇌ Na<sup>+</sup> (out) + 2H<sup>+</sup> (in).</blockquote>

